<TEXT type="str">Ottawa, January 29 ( QNA ) - Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau has told refugees to come to Canada, after US President Donald Trump suspended his country&apos;s refugee programme for four months. 
&quot;To those fleeing persecution, terror and war, Canadians will welcome you, regardless of your faith. Diversity is our strength,&quot; Trudeau tweeted on Saturday. 
He also posted a picture of himself welcoming a Syrian girl at Toronto airport in December 2015, the (dpa) reported. 
On Friday, Trump signed an executive order imposing what he calls &quot;extreme vetting&quot; on refugees and banning all travelers from six countries ( Iraq, Syria, Sudan, Libya, Yemen and Somalia) for 90 days. 
Canada has a history of welcoming refugees and as of January has settled almost 40,000 Syrians fleeing the current conflict. ( QNA )</TEXT> 
